04690nam a22007215i 9781400823956DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20122000nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984688333  a97814008239567 a10.1515/97814008239562doi  a(DE-B1597)453622  a(OCoLC)979834480  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aD613 7aHIS0270902bisacsh04a940.4/39a940.4391 aGoemans, H. E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar and Punishment :bThe Causes of War Termination and the First World War /cH. E. Goemans.  aCore Textbook 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b2 line illus., 20 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in International History and Politics ;v13600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF TABLES AND FIGURES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. INTRODUCTION -- t2. A THEORY OF WAR TERMINATION -- t3. LARGE N: THE FATE OF LEADERS AND THE DURATION OF WAR -- t4. GERMANY -- t5. RUSSIA -- t6. FRANCE -- t7. GREAT BRITAIN -- t8. THE TERMINATION OF THE FIRST WORLD WAR, I: 1914-1917 -- t9. THE TERMINATION OF THE FIRST WORLD WAR, II: 1918 -- t10. CONCLUSION -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat makes wars drag on and why do they end when they do? Here H. E. Goemans brings theoretical rigor and empirical depth to a long-standing question of securities studies. He explores how various government leaders assess the cost of war in terms of domestic politics and their own postwar fates. Goemans first develops the argument that two sides will wage war until both gain sufficient knowledge of the other's strengths and weaknesses so as to agree on the probable outcome of continued war. Yet the incentives that motivate leaders to then terminate war, Goemans maintains, can vary greatly depending on the type of government they represent. The author looks at democracies, dictatorships, and mixed regimes and compares the willingness among leaders to back out of wars or risk the costs of continued warfare. Democracies, according to Goemans, will prefer to withdraw quickly from a war they are not winning in order to appease the populace. Autocracies will do likewise so as not to be overthrown by their internal enemies. Mixed regimes, which are made up of several competing groups and which exclude a substantial proportion of the people from access to power, will likely see little risk in continuing a losing war in the hope of turning the tide. Goemans explores the conditions and the reasoning behind this "gamble for resurrection" as well as other strategies, using rational choice theory, statistical analysis, and detailed case studies of Germany, Britain, France, and Russia during World War I. In so doing, he offers a new perspective of the Great War that integrates domestic politics, international politics, and battlefield developments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCapitulations, Military. 0aPeace treaties. 0aPeace. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xArmistices. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082395640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400823956423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400823956.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK